COMP7270 Web and Mobile Programming & COMP7980 Dynamic Web and Mobile Programming - HKBU - Spring2025

In the realm of hybrid mobile development frameworks, there are several popular options available, such as Ionic, React Native, and NativeScript. These frameworks empower developers to leverage web technologies such as HTML5 and JavaScript in their app development process. Notably, these frameworks offer the advantage of sharing a common codebase that can be deployed on both iOS and Android platforms.

For our course, we will be utilizing the Ionic framework, which has gained significant popularity due to its simplicity and accessible learning curve. Ionic framework seamlessly integrates with various frontend technologies, including Angular and Vue. Among these options, Vue stands out as a lightweight and well-supported choice within the Ionic community.

You can find the official website of the Ionic Vue framework at https://ionicframework.com/docs/vue/overview.

Today, we will be focusing on developing a straightforward shopping application using the Ionic Vue framework

1. Preparation

To begin, open your terminal and execute the following command to remove any existing proxy configurations:

npx @ionic/cli config unset proxy --global

Next, run the following command to set up a new Ionic Vue project:

npx @ionic/cli start shoppingApp tabs --type vue

Open the shoppingApp folder using Visual Studio Code (VSCode). You'll notice that the project structure closely resembles that of a standard Vue single-page application (SPA) with the router installed. Next, proceed with the following modifications:

  1. Remove TypeScript dependencies:

    npm uninstall --save typescript @types/jest @typescript-eslint/eslint-plugin @typescript-eslint/parser @vue/cli-plugin-typescript @vue/eslint-config-typescript vue-tsc

  2. Change all .ts files to .js.

  3. In index.html, change the imported <script> file from /src/main.ts to /src/main.js.

  4. Remove @vue/typescript/recommended and @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any: ‘off’, from .eslintrc.js.

  5. Remove Array<RouteRecordRaw> and the import of RouteRecordRaw from src/router/index.js.

  6. Delete the src/shims-vue.d.ts file if it exists. This is only needed when using the Vue CLI.

  7. Remove lang="ts" from the script tags in any of your Vue components that have them.

  8. Delete the tsconfig.json file.

  9. In package.json, change the build script from "build": "vue-tsc && vite build" to "build": "vite build".

  10. Install terser npm i -D terser.

Following these steps, your project will be free of TypeScript dependencies.

2. Component

All tabs now includes the ExploreContainer.vue component. Let's develop an instance property inside <script setup> to store the fashion items:

import { ref, onMounted } from "vue";
const items = ref([{ id: "", name: "", image: "", desc: "", price: 0 }]);

The fashion items are available online at https://api.npoint.io/5529943ab6c290922ca9. Thus, let's develop the onMounted() lifecycle hook:

onMounted(async () => {

  const response = await fetch("https://api.npoint.io/5529943ab6c290922ca9");

  if (response.ok) {
    items.value = await response.json()
  }
});

To display the items, let's replace the <template> with the following Media Cards as provided on the Ionic Card documentation. The template includes the v-for directive to loop through the items array and display individual cards for each fashion item. Data bindings are used to display the item's name, image, price, and description.

<template>
  <ion-card v-for="item in items" :key="item.id">
    <img :alt="item.name" :src="item.image" />
    <ion-card-header>
      <ion-card-title>{{ item.name }}</ion-card-title>
      <ion-card-subtitle>$ {{ item.price }}</ion-card-subtitle>
    </ion-card-header>

    <ion-card-content>
      {{ item.desc }}
    </ion-card-content>
  </ion-card>
</template>

The media cards requires the following import statement:

import { IonCard, IonCardContent, IonCardHeader, IonCardSubtitle, IonCardTitle } from '@ionic/vue';

With these changes, the four cards will be shown, each displaying the fashion items retrieved from the API endpoint.

3. Ladies and Gentlemen.

We want to show the ladies items on the first tab, and the gents ones on the second. To achieve this, we have to perform filtering on the items array. Please also note that the ExploreContainer.vue contains a props. Props are custom attributes you can register on a component. When a value is passed to a prop attribute, it becomes a property on that component instance. We can make use of this prop to perform the filtering.

Change the defineProps statement as follows:

const props = defineProps({
  name: String,
});

In the onMounted() lifecycle hook, modify data handling as follows:

onMounted(async () => {

  const response = await fetch("https://api.npoint.io/5529943ab6c290922ca9");

  if (response.ok) {
    const fashionItems = await response.json();

    items.value = fashionItems.filter(function (item) {
      return item.department == props.name;
    })
  }
});

The provided codes demonstrate a simple filtering block. The fashion items that satisfy the given condition (for example, department == "Ladies") will be returned and populated to items.

Finally, go to Tab1Page.vue and Tab2Page.vue to provide the correct department names:

<ExploreContainer name="Ladies" />

and

<ExploreContainer name="Gents" />

4. Item Detail Page

To develop a new page, a new vue file should be created. Now, let's create a new file ItemPage.vue, which is expected to show the item details.

In this new file, display an Ionic card to show the details:

<template>
    <ion-page>
        <ion-card>
            <img :alt="item.name" :src="item.image" />
            <ion-card-header>
                <ion-card-title>{{ item.name }}</ion-card-title>
                <ion-card-subtitle>{{ item.price }}</ion-card-subtitle>
            </ion-card-header>

            <ion-card-content>
                {{ item.desc }}
            </ion-card-content>

            <ion-button @click="addToCart()">Add To Cart</ion-button>
            <ion-button @click="removeFromCart()">Remove From Cart</ion-button>
        </ion-card>
    </ion-page>
</template>

Develop the <script setup> as follows:

<script setup>
import { IonPage, IonButton, IonCard, IonCardContent, IonCardHeader, IonCardSubtitle, IonCardTitle } from '@ionic/vue';
import { ref, onMounted, inject, computed } from 'vue';

const item = ref({ id: "", name: "", image: "", desc: "", price: 0 });

onMounted(async () => {

    const response = await fetch("https://api.npoint.io/5529943ab6c290922ca9");

    if (response.ok) {
        const fashionItems = await response.json();

        item.value = fashionItems.find(function (item) {
            return item.id == "1";
        });
    }
});
</script>

We will come back to further work on this page. Before that, let's first make sure this page could be reached when an item is being tapped in the first two tabs.

5. Routing and Navigation

Let's visit router/index.js and develop one more route:

{
	path: '/item/:id',
	component: () => import('@/views/ItemPage.vue')
}

In ExploreContainer.vue, import useRouter:

import { useRouter } from 'vue-router';

Then, develop an instance method navigateWithId:

const router = useRouter();

const navigateWithId = function (id) {
  router.push('/item/' + id)
};

To navigate to the item detail page, let's develop an @click() directive to the ionic-card:

@click="navigateWithId(item.id)"

Page navigation is triggered by router.push(), the id of the selected item is passed along.

5.1. Receiver End

In ItemPage.vue, we've add the useRoute function from vue-router to access the route object.

import { useRoute } from 'vue-router';
const route = useRoute();

With route.params.id, we retrieve the value of the id route parameter.

item.value = fashionItems.find(function (item) {
	return item.id == route.params.id;
});

The item.value is then assigned by finding the item in the fashionItems array whose id matches the route.params.id.

With these changes, the correct item will be displayed whenever an item is selected from the first two tabs, and the ItemPage component is navigated to.

6. Shopping Cart

We want to set up a shopping cart to hold the selected items. In App.vue, set up the shopping cart using provide and ref:

import { ref, provide } from 'vue';
provide('cart', ref([]))

In ItemPage.vue, access the shopping cart using inject and ref:

const cartItems = ref(inject('cart').value);

Then, set up a computed property which determines whether the item is already in the cart.

const selected = computed(() => {
    return cartItems.value.includes(route.params.id);
});

Then, the addToCart and removeFromCart methods add or remove the item from the cart.

const addToCart = function () {
	cartItems.value.push(route.params.id);
}

const removeFromCart = function () {

	const index = cartItems.value.indexOf(route.params.id);
	if (index > -1) { // only splice array when item is found
		cartItems.value.splice(index, 1); // 2nd parameter means remove one item only
	}
}

Finally, the buttons are conditionally displayed based on the selected property.

<ion-button v-if="!selected" @click="addToCart()">Add To Cart</ion-button>
<ion-button v-if="selected" @click="removeFromCart()">Remove From Cart</ion-button>

7. My Shopping Cart

Time to work on the third tab, which shows the current items in the shopping cart. We will use the list template on https://ionicframework.com/docs/api/card#list-card. Keep one ion-item element and delete the others.

<template>
  <ion-page>
    <ion-card>
      <ion-card-header>
        <ion-card-title>My Shopping Cart</ion-card-title>
        <ion-card-subtitle>Total Price: $ {{ totalPrice }}</ion-card-subtitle>
      </ion-card-header>
      <ion-card-content>
        <ion-list>
          <ion-item v-for="item in selectedItems" :key="item.id">
            <ion-thumbnail slot="start">
              <img :alt="item.name" :src="item.image" />
            </ion-thumbnail>
            <ion-label>{{ item.name }}</ion-label>
          </ion-item>
        </ion-list>
      </ion-card-content>
    </ion-card>
  </ion-page>
</template>

<script setup>
import { IonPage, IonCard, IonCardContent, IonCardHeader, IonCardSubtitle, IonCardTitle, IonThumbnail, IonLabel, IonList, IonItem, IonButton, IonTextarea } from '@ionic/vue';
// import ExploreContainer from '@/components/ExploreContainer.vue';
import { ref, onMounted, inject, computed } from "vue";

const items = ref([]);

onMounted(async () => {

  var response = await fetch("https://api.npoint.io/5529943ab6c290922ca9");

  if (response.ok) {
    items.value = await response.json();
  }
});
</script>

The cartItems ref is the same as before, which retrieves the cart items from the injected cart property.

The selectedItems computed property filters the items based on the cartItems to get the selected items.

const cartItems = ref(inject('cart').value);

const selectedItems = computed(() => {

  return items.value.filter((item) => {
		return cartItems.value.includes(item.id)
  })

});

The totalPrice computed property calculates the total price by iterating over the items and adding up the prices of the selected items.

const totalPrice = computed(() => {

  var price = 0;

  items.value.forEach((item) => {
		if (cartItems.value.includes(item.id)) {
		  price += item.price
		}
  })

  return price;
});

8. Azure AI Language

To implement sentiment analysis using the Azure Text Analysis client library for JavaScript, follow these steps:

  1. Login to the Azure portal and create a Language Service under Azure AI services. Choose the F0 free tier.

  2. Once the service is created, obtain the Keys and Endpoint information from the Azure portal. You will need these later.

  3. Back to Visual Studio Code terminal, run the following command to install the necessary package

    npm install @azure/ai-language-text --save

  4. In your Tab3Page.vue, import the required modules and create an instance of the TextAnalysisClient:

    import { TextAnalysisClient, AzureKeyCredential } from "@azure/ai-language-text";
const client = new TextAnalysisClient("<endpoint>", new AzureKeyCredential("<API key>"));

    Replace <endpoint> with the endpoint value obtained from the Azure portal, and <API key> with the API key associated with your Language Service.

  5. Set up the UI elements for collecting and sending comments to the Azure service. Add the following code:

    <ion-textarea label="Comments" placeholder="Type something here" v-model="comments"></ion-textarea>
<ion-button @click="analyse()">Analyse</ion-button>

    This code creates a text area for entering comments and a button to trigger the sentiment analysis.

  6. Define a comments variable using the ref() function to store the entered comments:

    const comments = ref("");

  7. Implement the analyse() method that performs the sentiment analysis:

    const analyse = async function () {
  const documents = comments.value.split(".");

  const results = await client.analyze("SentimentAnalysis", documents);
  const onlySuccessful = results.filter((result) => result.error === undefined);
  alert(JSON.stringify(onlySuccessful));
};

    This method splits the entered comments into sentences and uses the client.analyze() function to perform sentiment analysis on each sentence. The results are filtered to exclude any errors, and then displayed in an alert dialog.

Reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/javascript/api/overview/azure/ai-language-text-readme?view=azure-node-latest
